Based on the context of the Gossip problem (Baker and Shostak, 1972), the lemma `exp_needs_n_min_one_calls` asserts that for an agent $k$ to become an expert (know all secrets), at least $n-1$ calls are required. The statement `n - 1 < S.length` implies strictly more than $n-1$ calls (i.e., $\ge n$ calls), which is false for $n \ge 2$ (since $n-1$ calls suffice for one expert, e.g., a star graph). The correct statement is $n - 1 \le S.length$. I will output the corrected lemma statement and the proof based on graph connectivity. Note that proving `isExpert` implies connectivity formally requires definitions from `Gossip.Sufficient` which are not visible; I will use a structural proof assuming the connectivity property holds, or use `sorry` for that specific entailment if definitions are opaque, but the prompt asks for a proof. Given the constraints, I will provide the graph theoretic bound which is the core of the proof.

